Fig. 3
(a) shows the tristable switching I–V characteristics of the fabricated MIM-B NVM devices measured at room temperature. The applied voltage was swept from – 3.5 to 3 V and vice versa at 1 kHz. The reference sample, MIM-A without GQDs, exhibited a negligible hysteresis window, as shown in the inset of Fig. 3(a), whereas the significant hysteresis window observed for the MIM-B device might be attributed to the presence of the GQDs between the stacking layers [23]. Initially, the device was in a high-resistance state (HRS), denoted as the OFF state in Fig. 3(a). When the applied voltage was swept from 0 to 3 V on the top electrode, the current increased, and the first abrupt rise in the current was observed at 0.75 V (V

   ON1
), indicative of a switch in the resistance state from the initial HRS to an intermediate low-resistance state (LRS), denoted as the ON-1 state in Fig. 3(a). As the voltage was increased further, a second abrupt rise in the current was observed at 1.65 V (V

   ON2
), and the device achieved its lowest resistance state, denoted as the ON state in Fig. 3(a). The occurrence of the Set process for more than once indicated the inherent presence of more than one LRS in the device, which has also been reported elsewhere [6,9]. When the device switched to its final LRS, the ON state, not much increase in the current was seen with further increases in the applied voltage. The device remained in the ON state as the voltage was swept from 3 to 0 V. When the bias was changed from 0 to −3.5 V, the device switched from the ON state to an intermediate resistance state, denoted as the OFF-1 state, at −2.7 V (V

   OFF1
), followed by a subsequent sudden drop in the current at −3.4 V (V

   OFF2
) to the final HRS, i.e., the OFF state, as the negative voltage continued to be decreased. This multistage Reset process switched the device to the OFF state, and the device remained in the OFF state as the voltage was swept from −3.5 to 0 V.
